
================================================================
SCOPY v1.0 - Smart Copy for CP/M 2.2
Technical Reference
================================================================


1. BUILD PROCEDURE

1.1. Requirements

   - Microsoft M80 Macro Assembler (M80.COM)
   - Microsoft L80 Linker (L80.COM)
   - Python 3 (for CPMFMT.PY source formatter)

1.2. Source Files

   SCOPY.MAC    Main (and only) assembly source file
   CPMFMT.PY    Converts source to CP/M text format
                (CR/LF line endings, Ctrl-Z EOF)

1.3. Build Steps

   On the CP/M system:

     M80 =SCOPY
     L80 SCOPY,SCOPY/N/E

   Using the DOS build script:

     build-all.bat

   The build script runs CPMFMT.PY automatically,
   then invokes M80 and L80 via cpmulator.exe.

1.4. CP/M Submit File

   BUILD.SUB can be used on the CP/M system:

     SUBMIT BUILD


2. PROGRAM STRUCTURE

   SCOPY is a single-file 8080 assembly program
   assembled with M80 into a CP/M .COM transient
   command. All code, data, and buffers reside in
   a single source file (SCOPY.MAC).

2.1. Memory Map

   0000H-0007H   Warm boot vector, IOBYTE, drive
   0005H-0007H   BDOS entry (JMP + address)
   0080H-00FFH   Command tail / default DMA buffer
   0100H         Program entry point (ORG 100H)
   ....H         Code section
   ....H         Message strings
   ....H         Data variables
   ....H         FCBs (TABFCB, WRKFCB, DIRFCB,
                       SFCB, DFCB)
   ....H         DMA buffer (128 bytes)
   ....H         TAB match list (64 x 11 = 704 bytes)
   ....H         File list (128 x 11 = 1408 bytes)
   ....H         Stack (128 bytes, 64 levels)
   BUFST         Copy buffer start (label at end of
                 data; extends to BDOS base)
   ....H         BDOS base (address from 0006H)

   The copy buffer dynamically uses all free TPA
   memory between the end of the program's data and
   the BDOS entry point.


3. FUNCTION REFERENCE

3.1. Main Flow

   MAIN
     Program entry point. Sets up the stack, saves
     the current drive and user area, displays the
     version banner, parses the command line, and
     dispatches to the appropriate mode (command line
     or interactive).

   VALID
     Central validation and execution entry point.
     Called after source and destination have been
     parsed (from either command line or interactive
     mode). Runs all validation checks, pre-flight
     capacity analysis, displays the summary, and
     invokes the copy engine.

3.2. System State

   GSTATE
     Saves the current drive (BDOS 25) in CDRV and
     the current user area (BDOS 32) in CUSR. Called
     once at startup.

   SETSRC
     Sets the source user area and drive. Resolves
     NSPC values to the saved current state.

   SETDST
     Sets the destination user area and drive.

   SETSU
     Sets only the source user area. Resolves NSPC
     to CUSR. Used during copy operations where the
     FCB drive byte handles drive selection.

   SETDU
     Sets only the destination user area.

   RESTOR
     Restores the original user area and drive from
     CUSR and CDRV.

   RSLVSD
     Returns the resolved source drive number + 1
     (for use as FCB byte 0). Resolves NSPC to CDRV.

   RSLVDD
     Returns the resolved dest drive number + 1.

3.3. Command Line Parsing

   CHKHLP
     Scans the command tail for /?. Returns carry
     set if found.

   SKPSPC
     Advances HL/B past space characters. Returns
     the next non-space character in A, or 0 if the
     input is exhausted.

   PSPEC
     Parses a file specification from the command
     tail or interactive input. Handles the full
     [user]drive:filename.ext syntax including the
     "." shorthand for current drive/user. Uses
     TXTPT/TXTCNT for input position and TGTPT for
     the 13-byte output block (user, drive, 11-byte
     filename). Returns carry on parse error.

   PDEC
     Parses a 1-2 digit decimal number from text.
     Used for user area numbers. Returns value in A,
     carry set on error.

   PFLAGS
     Parses option flags (/V, /C, /R, /Q) from the
     remaining command tail. Sets the corresponding
     flag bytes. Returns carry on unknown flag.

   TOUPR
     Converts ASCII character in A to uppercase.

   CHKFN
     Checks if an 11-byte filename area is all
     spaces (no filename specified). Returns carry
     if all spaces.

3.4. Validation

   CHKWRN
     Checks for wildcards in the source combined
     with a rename destination. Returns carry if
     both are present (invalid combination).

   CHKSLF
     Checks that the source and destination do not
     resolve to the same drive, user area, and
     filename. Resolves NSPC defaults before
     comparing. Returns carry if self-copy detected.

   VDSTFN
     Validates characters in the destination filename.
     Rejects wildcards (*, ?) and CP/M invalid
     characters (<, >, comma, semicolon, colon, =,
     brackets, pipe, backslash, control chars).
     Returns carry with BADCHR set if invalid.

3.5. Interactive Mode

   GETLIN
     Line editor for interactive input. Reads
     characters one at a time using BDOS 6 (Direct
     Console I/O) to intercept TAB before the BDOS
     line editor processes it. Handles printable
     characters, backspace, DELETE, CR, CTRL-C,
     and TAB. Stores input in LINBUF, length in
     LINLEN. Converts all input to uppercase.

   TABCMP
     TAB completion handler. On first press: calls
     TPARSE to analyze the input, then TABSRC to
     search the directory. Caches matches and
     displays the first one. On subsequent presses:
     cycles to the next match (circular). Rings
     the bell if no matches or if wildcards are
     present.

   TPARSE
     Parses LINBUF to extract the TAB completion
     context: user area, drive, and partial filename.
     Builds a search FCB (TABFCB) with the partial
     name padded with ? characters. Always resolves
     the FCB drive byte explicitly (never uses
     default drive 0). Sets PFXLEN to the length of
     the [user]drive: prefix that stays on screen
     during completion cycling.

   TABSRC
     Searches the directory for TAB completion
     matches. Sets the user area and drive, uses
     DMABUF for directory I/O, and fills TABMAT
     with deduplicated 11-byte filenames. Strips
     attribute high bits. Restores user/drive on
     return. Maximum 64 matches (MAXTAB).

3.6. Pre-Flight (Phase 3)

   EXPAND
     Expands the source wildcard into a file list.
     Searches the source directory using WRKFCB,
     deduplicates multi-extent files (via ISDUPF),
     fills FLIST with 11-byte filenames, counts
     total directory extents in SRCEXT. Maximum
     128 files (MAXFLS). Jumps to ERRNOF if no
     files match.

   CALCSZ
     Calculates the total source file size in KB.
     Iterates through FLIST, uses BDOS 35 (Compute
     File Size) for each file to get the record
     count, converts to KB via (records+7)/8, and
     accumulates in TOTSIZ.

   CHKDST
     Checks destination disk capacity. Reads the
     Disk Parameter Block (BDOS 31) to extract BSH,
     DSM, and DRM. Gets the allocation vector
     (BDOS 27) and counts free blocks (CNTFRE).
     Converts to free KB using the block shift
     factor. Counts free directory entries (CNTDIR).
     Compares source needs against destination
     capacity. Jumps to ERRSPC or ERRDIE on
     failure.

   CNTFRE
     Counts free blocks in the allocation vector.
     Walks bit-by-bit through (DSM+1) bits. A zero
     bit indicates a free block. Stores the count
     in FREBKS.

   CNTDIR
     Counts free directory entries on the destination
     disk. Uses the FCB byte 0 = '?' trick to search
     across all user areas in a single pass. Filters
     out deleted entries (user byte = E5H). Computes
     free = (DRM+1) - used. Stores in DSTDIR.

3.7. Copy Engine (Phase 4)

   DOCOPY
     Main copy orchestrator. Calculates the copy
     buffer size from available TPA memory (BUFST
     to BDOS base). Iterates through FLIST, handling
     /C confirmation, /Q quiet mode, overwrite
     prompting, and file creation. For each file,
     runs the multi-pass copy loop, closes files,
     copies attributes, optionally verifies, and
     updates counters. Displays per-file status
     and a final summary.

     Buffer size calculation:
       Buffer end = [0006H] - 1 (one below BDOS)
       Buffer size = BUFEND - BUFST
       Records per buffer = size / 128

     Copy is performed by record count (BDOS 35),
     NOT by scanning for Ctrl-Z EOF markers. This
     ensures binary files are copied correctly.

   Multi-pass copy loop:
     For each pass:
       1. Calculate records this pass =
          min(BUFREC, RECREQ)
       2. Set source user area
       3. Read all records into buffer (BUFST),
          advancing DMA by 128 per record
       4. Set destination user area
       5. Write all records from buffer,
          advancing DMA by 128 per record
       6. Subtract records copied from RECREQ
       7. Repeat until RECREQ = 0

   BLDSFCB
     Builds the source FCB (SFCB) from CPYFN with
     the resolved source drive in byte 0.

   BLDDFCB
     Builds the destination FCB (DFCB) from DSTFN
     with the resolved dest drive in byte 0.

   BLDWFCB
     Builds WRKFCB from CPYFN for use with BDOS 35
     (Compute File Size).

   CPYATT
     Copies file attributes from source to dest.
     Searches the source directory to read the R/O,
     SYS, and Archive attribute bits (high bit of
     extension bytes t1, t2, t3). Applies them to
     the destination file using BDOS 30 (Set File
     Attributes).

   DOVERFY
     Verifies a copied file by read-back comparison.
     Reopens both source and destination files, reads
     one record at a time from each into BUFST and
     BUFST+128, and compares 128 bytes. Returns
     carry set if any mismatch is found.

   GETYN
     Reads a Y/N response using BDOS 6 (no echo),
     converts to uppercase, echoes the result.
     Returns 'Y' or 'N' in A.

3.8. Display Routines

   SHSUM
     Displays the pre-flight summary showing source
     file count and total size, destination free
     space and free directory entries.

   SHFNL
     Formats and displays an 11-byte FCB filename
     to the console as NAME.EXT (via FMTFN).

   FMTFN
     Formats an 11-byte FCB filename into a NAME.EXT
     string in a buffer. Trims trailing spaces from
     both name and extension. Returns the formatted
     length in A.

   SHFN
     Displays an 11-byte FCB filename directly to
     the console with trailing space trimming.

   SHUSR
     Displays a user number in brackets: [N].
     Resolves NSPC to the current user.

   SHDRV
     Displays a drive letter with colon: D:.
     Resolves NSPC to the current drive.

   DECOUT
     Prints register A as a decimal number (0-255)
     with leading zero suppression.

   DEC16
     Prints register pair HL as a decimal number
     (0-65535) with leading zero suppression. Uses
     repeated subtraction for each decimal position.

   COUT
     Outputs character in A to the console via
     BDOS 2. Preserves all registers.

   CRLF
     Outputs a carriage return and line feed.

   PRMSG
     Prints a $-terminated string via BDOS 9.

   ERASCR
     Erases A characters from the console by sending
     backspace-space-backspace sequences.

3.9. Utility Routines

   MUL11
     Multiplies A by 11, result in HL. Used for
     indexing into 11-byte filename tables (TABMAT,
     FLIST). Computes as A*8 + A*3 using DAD.

   SHR16
     Logical shift right of HL by 1 bit. Used
     three times in sequence for division by 8
     (records to KB conversion).

   ISDUPE
     Checks if TMPFN (11 bytes) already exists in
     TABMAT. Returns carry if duplicate found.
     Used during TAB completion to skip multi-extent
     directory entries.

   ISDUPF
     Same as ISDUPE but checks against FLIST/FCNT.
     Used during wildcard expansion.


4. BDOS FUNCTIONS USED

   0    System Reset (warm boot on exit)
   1    Console Input (not currently used)
   2    Console Output (character display)
   6    Direct Console I/O (line editor, Y/N input)
   9    Print String ($-terminated)
   14   Select Disk
   15   Open File
   16   Close File
   17   Search for First
   18   Search for Next
   19   Delete File
   20   Read Sequential
   21   Write Sequential
   22   Make File (create)
   25   Return Current Disk
   26   Set DMA Address
   27   Get Allocation Vector Address
   30   Set File Attributes
   31   Get Disk Parameter Block Address
   32   Set/Get User Code
   35   Compute File Size


5. KEY DATA STRUCTURES

   Source/Dest File Spec (13 bytes each):
     Byte 0     User number (0-15, or FFH=current)
     Byte 1     Drive number (0-15, or FFH=current)
     Bytes 2-12 Filename in FCB format (8+3, space
                padded)

   File List (FLIST, 128 x 11 bytes):
     Array of matched source filenames in 8+3 FCB
     format. Deduplicated (no multi-extent repeats).
     Indexed by FCNT.

   TAB Match List (TABMAT, 64 x 11 bytes):
     Array of filenames matching the TAB completion
     partial input. Indexed by TABCNT/TABIDX.

   FCBs (36 bytes each):
     Standard CP/M File Control Blocks used for
     BDOS file operations. Byte 0 is always set to
     the explicit drive code (1=A, 2=B, etc.),
     never left as 0 (default).

   Copy Buffer (BUFST to BUFEND):
     Dynamically sized at runtime. Uses all TPA
     between the end of program data and the BDOS
     base address. Size is calculated as:
       BUFEND = [0006H] - 1
       Records = (BUFEND - BUFST) / 128


6. DESIGN DECISIONS

   Binary-safe copying:
     Files are copied by record count obtained from
     BDOS 35 (Compute File Size), not by scanning
     for Ctrl-Z (1AH) EOF markers. Binary files
     such as .COM executables may contain embedded
     1AH bytes as valid data.

   Explicit drive resolution:
     FCB byte 0 is always set to the explicit drive
     code rather than 0 (default drive). This avoids
     issues with some CP/M implementations where
     the default drive does not resolve correctly
     after a user area change.

   Pre-flight space checking:
     All source files are enumerated and their total
     size calculated before any copying begins. The
     destination's free space and directory entries
     are checked against the total requirements.
     This prevents partial copies that would leave
     the destination in an inconsistent state.

   User area switching:
     During copy operations, only the user area is
     switched between read and write passes. The
     FCB drive byte handles drive selection,
     avoiding unnecessary SELDSK calls. User area
     is always set explicitly (NSPC resolved to
     saved CUSR), never left to chance.

   Directory deduplication:
     Files spanning multiple directory extents
     produce multiple search results. Both the TAB
     completion and wildcard expansion routines
     check for duplicate filenames before adding
     to their respective lists. Attribute high bits
     are stripped before comparison.


================================================================
END OF TECHNICAL REFERENCE
